{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_017xhaGsmjeQk38mpPgsJRhF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The new worker pods are in CrashLoopBackOff! The container is in a waiting state because it's backing off from restarting. The error is \"back-off 40s restarting failed container.\" \n\nSo the pods show as \"Running\" and \"1/1 Ready\" in the basic pod listing, but they're actually in CrashLoopBackOff. The \"Ready\" state was from the previous run cycle and hasn't been updated.\n\nWait, but the pod listing showed:\n```\nray-worker-7d7d685797-7dc6w   1/1     Running   2 (3m22s ago)   8m24s\n```\n\nAnd now it's in CrashLoopBackOff. The status hasn't refreshed.\n\nThis is the core issue. The new worker pods keep crashing with \"Failed to connect to GCS.\" They're trying to reach `ray-head:6379` which routes to port 10001 (the Ray client server) on the head pod, but the GCS actually runs on port 6379 directly. So why do the original workers (t7qhh, wsqhm) connect successfully when they're using the same address? I need to look more carefully at the head pod IP and how the service is routing traffic.\n\nThe service ClusterIP is `10.96.164.243` and the endpoints show `10.244.0.182:10001`. When workers resolve `ray-head:6379`, it goes to the service IP which maps to the head pod's port 10001. But when I tested from inside the head pod using `127.0.0.1:6379`, the GCS was actually open there. Maybe the original workers are somehow bypassing the service and connecting directly to the pod IP instead? Or perhaps `ray-head` resolves to the pod IP directly through Kubernetes DNS in the same namespace?\n\n```\nActually, wait — the service IS named `ray-head`, and the pod is `ray-head-7c665f5784-9ts7d`. In the same namespace, `ray-head` resolves to the service ClusterIP `10.96.164.243`, not the pod. So all workers connecting to `ray-head:6379` hit port 10001 on the head pod, which is the Ray client server. Connecting a worker to the client server would fail with \"Method not found\" on GCS gRPC calls.\n\nUnless in Ray 2.9.0, the `ray start --address=` command connects to the head node differently. The `--address` parameter should be the GCS server address, and the GCS server runs on port 6379 by default on the head node. Workers connect to GCS on this port.\n```\nBut the service is mapping external port 6379 to internal port 10001 — that's backwards for worker connections. The workers should connect directly to the head pod IP on port 6379, or the service should forward 6379 to 6379. Yet the original 2 workers are connected and working, so something doesn't add up.\n\nLet me reconsider what port the GCS gRPC server is actually running on inside the head pod.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1443,"cache_read_input_tokens":55460,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1443},"output_tokens":28,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"34abd7e5-b560-4ada-abf9-16e9c2b88f15","uuid":"1cba3d3f-6dbd-4942-a06f-81248d3c609b","request_id":"req_011Cc6eftD6H4P5XuakBxYym"}
