{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01GPjwvWLpSTdsUUmYdhnjq1","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So `ray-head` resolves to `10.96.164.243` (the ClusterIP), and port 6379 on the ClusterIP maps to port 10001 on the head pod. And the GcsClient Python API confirms that connecting to `ray-head:6379` gets \"Method not found.\"\n\nYet the original workers ARE connected to the Ray cluster (showing as active nodes). The only explanation I can think of is:\n\n1. The raylet binary uses a DIFFERENT gRPC service protocol than what GcsClient's `internal_kv_get` uses. The raylet connects to register as a node, while `internal_kv_get` is a different service.\n2. Port 10001 might handle both the Ray client server and some GCS gRPC calls, just not `internal_kv_get` specifically.\n3. In Ray 2.9.0, when `ray start --address` is called, it might first query the bootstrap node at port 10001 to get the actual GCS address (which handles a different set of gRPC methods), then connect to the real GCS. Looking at the service definition again, the port is named \"gcs\" but maps to target port 10001, which in KubeRay suggests this might be a routing layer rather than the actual GCS endpoint.\n\nThe head pod's port 10001 likely serves as a bootstrap port where workers first connect to discover the actual GCS address. In Ray 2.x, `--address` is used to locate the GCS server, while `--gcs-address` on the raylet points to the actual GCS gRPC endpoint—these might be the same or different. Since Ray 2.9.0 removed Redis and embedded the GCS with its own gRPC protocol, the bootstrap mechanism probably works differently than in older versions. Let me reconsider this from a different angle. The raylet successfully discovered the cluster ID through the service on port 6379, so the discovery protocol is working. When the raylet connects to the GCS for node registration using `--gcs-address=ray-head:6379`, it's also routing through the same service mapping.\n\nThe real puzzle is that port 10001 (the Ray client server) handles different gRPC methods than the GCS—`internal_kv_get` fails there with \"Method not found\"—yet the raylet might be using different methods that ARE available on that port. But if the original workers succeeded, the service port mapping isn't the culprit for the new workers failing. Something else in the bootstrap timeline must be different.\n\nLooking at the logs, the original workers each restarted exactly once around 5 minutes after startup, while the new workers crash repeatedly starting at 01:37. I should check what caused that first crash for the original workers—if they also hit \"Failed to connect to GCS\" initially, what made their second attempt succeed?","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":572,"cache_read_input_tokens":63816,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":572},"output_tokens":43,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"34abd7e5-b560-4ada-abf9-16e9c2b88f15","uuid":"29ca6390-6b2c-47d1-a78b-ed3b9635dea1","request_id":"req_011Cc6eo5HHgzLoCUo8ivEcZ"}
