{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_015MfTpvs4LxLiFfDmP5v5DL","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The original worker's FIRST run actually SUCCEEDED and connected to Ray at 01:10:56. But then it was terminated (SIGTERM, which is graceful) and restarted. \n\nThe head started at `01:15:42`. But the original worker's first run was at `01:10:56`, which is BEFORE the head started! This means the original worker started before the head pod existed, and then restarted after the head was ready.\n\nThat explains the pattern:\n1. Original workers started first (at 01:10:56) - tried to connect to a non-existent head\n2. They somehow connected successfully to an existing Ray cluster before the head pod came up\n3. Then got terminated and restarted after the new head was ready\n\nBut wait, this timeline doesn't add up. If the head logs show it started at 01:15:42 and the workers' first run was at 01:10:56, that's a 5-minute gap. I need to look more carefully at the cluster ID in the head logs to understand what's actually happening here.\n\nThe original workers must have connected to a different head instance that was running before the current one. When the head got redeployed at 01:15:42, the workers restarted and connected to the new head. But the new workers that started around 01:37 are having trouble connecting to this same cluster, which suggests there might be a session compatibility issue or something preventing them from joining. The workers are failing at the GCS connection step, but the original workers connected successfully even with the same `RAY_RAYLET_PID=1` environment variable set. Looking at the IP addresses, the new workers (10.244.0.185 and 10.244.0.186) are different from the original ones (10.244.0.177 and 10.244.0.178), so this might be a networking or DNS resolution issue preventing the new workers from reaching the head node's GCS port. The \"Method not found!\" error from GcsClient suggests the gRPC endpoint isn't exposing the expected GCS service methods. But I'm wondering if port 10001 on the head pod might actually be serving both Ray client and GCS operations in 2.9.0, or if it's something else entirely. Let me verify what's actually running on that port.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2062,"cache_read_input_tokens":64388,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2062},"output_tokens":22,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"34abd7e5-b560-4ada-abf9-16e9c2b88f15","uuid":"bd4c47fe-4a6b-4783-a949-97dd301c3179","request_id":"req_011Cc6eqaHrtrGuYyhmE9nFk"}
