{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_015x59kP3y6nr3VJDRKkV73r","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now it's crystal clear:\n\n- `ray-head:6379` (→ port 10001 on head pod): FAILS with \"Method not found\"\n- `10.244.0.182:6379` (direct pod IP, real GCS): SUCCEEDS, cluster_id = `18dffd0aadf29ba1efe8af19b886c10309986c2dacaaf7928d98a595`\n- `10.244.0.182:10001` (Ray client server directly): FAILS with \"Method not found\"\n\nSo `get_cluster_id()` fails when using `ray-head:6379` (ClusterIP → port 10001). \n\nBut wait—the original workers ARE connected to the cluster, yet when I tested `get_cluster_id()` from the original worker pod using `ray-head:6379`, it also failed. That means the worker didn't actually connect through that address. The raylet is configured with `--gcs-address=ray-head:6379`, but something else must be happening when I try to use `GcsClient('ray-head:6379')` from within the pod.\n\nI'm wondering if the raylet resolved `ray-head` to a different address at startup—maybe the head pod's direct IP instead of the ClusterIP. In Kubernetes, `ray-head` should resolve to the ClusterIP service unless there's a headless service involved, but I need to verify what actually happened when the original workers started right after the head was redeployed.\n\nThe raylet and Python's GcsClient might also be using different gRPC protocols or transport mechanisms—the raylet's C++ implementation could be using a Redis-compatible protocol while the Python client uses pure gRPC, which would explain why one works and the other fails.\n\nLooking at the Ray client server command with `--mode=proxy`, when a connection arrives on port 10001, it proxies to `10.244.0.182:6379`, but this proxy only handles the Ray client gRPC methods for remote `ray.init()`, not the GCS gRPC service that `GcsClient.get_cluster_id()` needs.\n\nI need to reconsider how the original workers actually connect—maybe the raylet connects to the bootstrap address and discovers the real GCS address from there, rather than using the provided `--gcs-address` directly.\n\nLet me check what connections the original worker's raylet has actually established to understand the real flow.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":553,"cache_read_input_tokens":81813,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":553},"output_tokens":25,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"34abd7e5-b560-4ada-abf9-16e9c2b88f15","uuid":"5071b591-a2bf-4b5a-a2f8-a8ec8b4080f1","request_id":"req_011Cc6f9wpfD8Xgop9Tu8jsH"}
