{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Au6XZKDStAcsjewDZrwFRU","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Important! Looking at the GCS stats again now (later timestamp `02:04:43`):\n- `NodeInfoGcsService.grpc_server.RegisterNode - 6 total` - still 6 total! No new registrations from the new workers (even though they've crashed multiple times)\n- `GcsServer.NodeDeathCallback - 3 total`\n\nSo the GCS RegisterNode count hasn't changed since the last check. This means the new workers, in their crash-loop, are NOT even reaching the GCS RegisterNode stage. They're failing in `_init_gcs_client` before `RegisterNode` is called.\nThe new workers are crashing during `_init_gcs_client()` when trying to connect to GCS at `ray-head:6379`, which is mapping to the wrong port. I could fix this by either updating the service port mapping or having workers connect directly to the head pod IP instead. I'm leaning toward patching the service, though I'm concerned it might disrupt the existing workers' connections.\n\nActually, thinking through this more carefully: the original workers have established TCP connections that are tracked by the kernel's conntrack table. If I change the service's TargetPort mapping, it only affects new connections going forward—the existing established connections will keep working through the conntrack rules. So if an original worker's GCS connection drops and reconnects, it would now correctly reach port 6379 instead of the wrong port. This is actually an improvement with minimal risk, so I should go ahead and patch the service.\n\nBut looking at the new worker logs, they're failing immediately without the expected retry warnings. Ray's GCS client should be attempting 20 retries with 1-second sleeps between them, which would only take about 20 seconds. Yet the container ran for 2.5 minutes before exiting. That suggests either there are many more retries happening than expected, or the connection timeout itself is adding significant delay to each attempt.\n\nI'm thinking the gRPC library might have its own connection timeout of around 5 seconds per attempt, which multiplied by 20 retries would get close to the 2.5-minute window I'm seeing. Regardless, all 20 retries are consistently failing with \"Method not found!\" errors.\n\nRather than debug further, I should just fix the service configuration. I could patch the worker deployment to connect directly to the head pod's IP address, but that's fragile since the IP changes on restarts. A better approach would be to update the service to properly map to the actual GCS port—either by changing the existing TargetPort from 10001 to 6379, or by adding a new service port that maps 6380 to 6379 and updating the worker command accordingly.\n\nOption 1 is cleaner, so I'll go with that. But wait—I need to think through why the original workers connected at all. They can't call `get_cluster_id()` through the service on port 6379, yet they're clearly connected to the Ray cluster somehow. If patching the service fixes the new workers, I need to understand what path the original workers took, or the patch might not actually solve the problem.\n\nThere are a few possible connection paths: the service ClusterIP mapping to port 10001 (which fails), the head pod IP directly (which works), or if we patch the service to map port 6379 directly. The new workers fail on path one, so patching should help them. But the original workers must have connected some other way—maybe during a window when DNS resolution failed and they fell back to the pod IP? I'm not entirely sure. Let me check the Ray client server logs to see if there's any record of proxied connections from the original workers at startup.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2763,"cache_read_input_tokens":108327,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemera